lessons.content:
@export exposes a variable in the Inspector panel. Instead of hardcoding values in your script, you set them per-instance in the editor. Same script, different Inspector values — completely different behavior.

This is powerful because it separates data from logic. An Enemy script with @export var speed: float = 100.0 can produce a slow patrol enemy at 80 and a fast charging enemy at 350 — same script, different Inspector configurations.

You can export most types: int, float, bool, String, Vector2, Color, NodePath, PackedScene, and custom Resource types.

@export_range(min, max) constrains a number to a slider in the Inspector. @export_enum("Idle", "Patrol", "Chase") creates a dropdown. @export_group("Combat") groups related exports under a collapsible header. These make your scripts much nicer to configure without touching code.

